-do better. "Civic engagement" has become an unwieldy and confusing catchall, Berger argues. We should talk instead of political, social, and moral engagement, figuring out which kinds of engagement make democracy work better, and how we might promote them. Focusing on political engagement and taking Alexis de Tocqueville and Hannah Arendt as his guides, Berger identifies ways to achieve the political engagement we want and need without resorting to coercive measures such as compulsory national service or mandatory voting. By providing a realistic account of the value of political engagement and practical strategies for improving it, while avoiding proposals we can never hope to achieve, Attention Deficit Democracy makes a persuasive case for a public philosophy that much of the public can actually endorse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aDemocracy. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  aAlexis de Tocqueville.  aHannah Arendt.  aattention deficit.  aattention.  acivic engagement.  acivil associations.  ademocracy.  aenergy.  ainstrumental good.  ainstrumental value.  aintrinsic good.  aintrinsic value.  ainvisibility.  aisolation.  aliberal democracy.  amaterialism.  amoral engagement.  aparticipatory democracy.  apolitical apathy.  apolitical associations.  apolitical education.  apolitical engagement.  apolitical governance.  apolitical institutions.  apolitical mobilization.  apolitics.  apublic freedom.  apublic philosophy.  aself-interest.  asocial engagement.  atotalitarianism.  atownship administration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400840311zCo-access 